05592nam a22008655i 9780674332874DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20131996mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013941759  a97806743328747 a10.4159/harvard.97806743328742doi  a(DE-B1597)248300  a(OCoLC)900806401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aMED0000002bisacsh1 aFujimura, Joan H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCrafting Science :bA Sociohistory of the Quest for the Genetics of Cancer /cJoan H. Fujimura.  aReprint 2014 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (322 p.) :b5 halftones, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Creating a New Realm -- tTools of the Trade: A Brief History of Standardized Experimental Systems in Cancer Research, 1920-1978 -- tMolecular Genetic Technologies: The New Tools of the Trade -- tCrafting Theory -- tDistributing Authority and Transforming Biology -- tProblems and Work Practices: Improvising on the Shop Floor -- tThe Articulation of Doable Problems in Cancer Research -- tConclusion: Crafting Oncogenes -- tAppendix: Social and Cultural Studies of Science -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the late 1970s and 1980s, "cancer" underwent a remarkable transformation. In one short decade, what had long been a set of heterogeneous diseases marked by uncontrolled cell growth became a disease of our genes. How this happened and what it means is the story Joan Fujimura tells in a rare inside look at the way science works and knowledge is created. A dramatic study of a new species of scientific revolution, this book combines a detailed ethnography of scientific thought, an in-depth account of science practiced and produced, a history of one branch of science as it entered the limelight, and a view of the impact of new genetic technologies on science and society. The scientific enterprise that Fujimura unfolds for us is proto-oncogene cancer research--the study of those segments of DNA now thought to make normal cells cancerous. Within this framework, she describes the processes of knowledge construction as a social enterprise, an endless series of negotiations in which theories, material technologies, and practices are co-constructed, incorporated, and refashioned. Along the way, Fujimura addresses long-standing questions in the history and philosophy of science, culture theory, and sociology of science: How do scientists create "good" problems, experiments, and solutions? What are the cultural, institutional, and material technologies that have to be in place for new truths and new practices to succeed? Portraying the development of knowledge as a multidimensional process conducted through multiple cultures, institutions, actors, objects, and practices, this book disrupts divisions among sociology, history, anthropology, and the philosophy of science, technology, and medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAnthropology, PhysicalzUnited States. 0aCulturevStudy and teaching. 0aCulturezUnited States. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aNeoplasmsvgeneticszUnited States. 0aProto-OncogenesvgeneticszUnited States. 0aProto-oncogenesvResearchvHistory. 0aResearchvhistoryzUnited States. 0aSciencevSocial aspects. 4aCancer -- Genetic aspects -- Research -- History. 4aMEDICAL / Oncology. 4aMedical anthropology. 4aSCIENCE / History. 4aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Genetics & Genomics. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB